The '''2014 National League Wild Card Game''' was a [[play-in game]] during [[Major League Baseball]]'s (MLB) [[2014 Major League Baseball season#Postseason|2014 postseason]] played between the [[National League]]'s (NL) two [[Major League Baseball wild card|wild card]] teams, the [[2014 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco Giants]] and the [[2014 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh Pirates]].  It was held at [[PNC Park]] in [[Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], on October 1, 2014, starting at 8:07&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]].<ref>{{cite news|title=MLB postseason: Playoff results and schedules through the World Series|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/early-lead/wp/2014/10/01/mlb-postseason-playoff-results-and-schedules-through-the-world-series/|date=October 1, 2014|first=Des|last=Bieler|accessdate=October 3, 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref>  After both teams finished the regular season with identical records of 88<U+2013>74,<ref>{{cite news|title=San Francisco Giants (88-74) at Pittsburgh Pirates (88-74), 8:07 p.m. (ET)|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2014/10/01/4197679/san-francisco-giants-88-74-at.html?sp=/99/103/123/|date=October 1, 2014|accessdate=October 6, 2014|newspaper=The News & Observer|location=Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref> the Pirates were awarded [[home advantage|home field]] for the game, as they won the season series against the Giants, four games to two.<ref>{{cite web|title=Possible tiebreaking scenarios explained|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/95341554/possible-tiebreaking-scenarios-explained|date=September 24, 2014|accessdate=October 6, 2014|first=Anthony|last=Castrovince|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Pirates win, clinch top wild card spot|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/27/bbo-pirates-reds-writethru-idUSMTZEA9RJFBR2V20140927|date=September 27, 2014|accessdate=October 6, 2014|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>  Despite this advantage, the Giants won by a score of 8<U+2013>0 and advanced to play the [[2014 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]] in the [[2014 National League Division Series|NL Division Series]] (NLDS).<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 MLB Postseason Schedule|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/schedule/ps.jsp?y=14|accessdate=October 3, 2014|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>  In addition to being the third NL Wild Card Game played, it is notable for the first [[Major League Baseball postseason|postseason]] [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] hit by a [[shortstop]].  The game was televised on [[ESPN Major League Baseball|ESPN]], and was also broadcast on [[Major League Baseball on ESPN Radio|ESPN Radio]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Start times announced for potential Tiebreaker, Wild Card Games|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/96817718/start-times-announced-for-potential-tiebreaker-wild-card-games|date=September 29, 2014|accessdate=October 3, 2014|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>

==Background==
{{main|2014 San Francisco Giants season|2014 Pittsburgh Pirates season}}
In Major League Baseball, the two teams with the best record in each league who do not win a [[Major League Baseball division winners|division]] play against each other in the [[Major League Baseball Wild Card Game|Wild Card Game]].  This was the second postseason meeting between the Giants and Pirates <U+2013> the two teams first met in the [[1971 National League Championship Series|1971 NL Championship Series]], with the Pirates coming from behind to win 3<U+2013>1 after dropping Game 1.<ref>{{cite web|title=1971 NLCS (3<U+2013>1): Pittsburgh Pirates (97<U+2013>65) over San Francisco Giants (90<U+2013>72)|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1971_NLCS.shtml|accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref>  The Giants' most recent [[Major League Baseball postseason|postseason]] appearance was in [[2012 Major League Baseball season|2012]], when they swept the [[Detroit Tigers]] to win the [[2012 World Series|World Series that year]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Giants' postseason streak a credit to consistent core|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/97677450/giants-postseason-win-streak-a-credit-to-consistent-core-of-players|date=October 5, 2014|accessdate=October 6, 2014|first=Anthony|last=DiComo|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>  On the other hand, the Pirates were able to advance to the playoffs in [[2013 Major League Baseball season|the previous season]], marking the team's first postseason appearance in 21 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pittsburgh Pirates Lock Up First MLB Playoff Berth in 21 Years|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-09-24/pittsburgh-pirates-lock-up-first-mlb-playoff-berth-in-21-years.html|date=September 24, 2013|accessdate=October 6, 2014|first=Erik|last=Matuszewski|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>  They lost 3<U+2013>2 in [[2013 National League Division Series|that year's NLDS]] to the [[St. Louis Cardinals]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stifled behind Cole, Bucs eliminated from postseason|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2013_10_09_pitmlb_slnmlb_1&mode=recap_away&c_id=pit|date=October 10, 2013|accessdate=October 6, 2014|first=Tom|last=Singer|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>

The first half of the [[2014 Major League Baseball season|2014 season]] ended with both teams having three players on the NL squad for the [[2014 Major League Baseball All-Star Game]].  [[Madison Bumgarner]], [[Tim Hudson]], and [[Hunter Pence]] represented the Giants,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/SFG/bat-all-star.shtml|title=San Francisco Giants All-Star Player Register|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 8, 2014}}</ref> while [[Josh Harrison]], [[Andrew McCutchen]], and [[Tony Watson]] represented the Pirates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/PIT/bat-all-star.shtml|title=Pittsburgh Pirates All-Star Player Register|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 8, 2014}}</ref>  During the second half of the season, there were several teams that were in contention for the two Wild Card spots, along with their divisional competition.  These included the [[Atlanta Braves]], [[Cincinnati Reds]], and [[Miami Marlins]], in addition to San Francisco and Pittsburgh.<ref>{{cite news|title=Giancarlo Stanton powers Miami Marlins' chase for NL wild card|url=http://www.si.com/mlb/2014/08/17/giancarlo-stanton-miami-marlins-playoff-chase|date=August 17, 2014|accessdate=October 8, 2014|first=Jon|last=Tayler|work=Sports Illustrated|publisher=Time Inc.}}</ref>  The Pirates performed poorly in August,<ref>{{cite news|title=In spite of struggles, Braves in tie for 2nd wild card spot|url=http://atlantabraves.blog.ajc.com/2014/09/05/in-spite-of-struggles-braves-in-tie-for-2nd-wild-card-spot/?__federated=1|date=September 5, 2014|first=David|last=O'Brien|accessdate=October 8, 2014|newspaper=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution}}</ref> and they lost seven consecutive games at one point.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pirates keep pace in playoff race with walk-off win|url=http://pittsburgh.pirates.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2014_08_20_atlmlb_pitmlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=pit|date=August 20, 2014|accessdate=October 8, 2014|first=Tom|last=Singer|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>  However, the team made a resurgence by winning 17 of the last 23 games of the regular season, surpassing San Francisco in the process for first place in the wild card standings.<ref>{{cite news|title=SF Giants heading to Pittsburgh for wild-card playoff|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/giants/2014/09/28/official-madison-bumgarner-to-start-wednesday-for-sf-giants-plus-start-time/|date=September 28, 2014|first=Henry|last=Schulman|accessdate=October 8, 2014|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>  The Pirates secured their spot in the postseason on September 23,<ref name=Buctober>{{cite web|title=Back to Buctober: Pirates rally to clinch spot|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2014_09_23_pitmlb_atlmlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=pit|date=September 23, 2014|accessdate=October 8, 2014|first=Tom|last=Singer|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref> while the Giants made it to the playoffs two days later.<ref name=clinch>{{cite web|title=Giants clinch Wild Card, then wait to celebrate|url=http://m.giants.mlb.com/news/article/96359014/giants-clinch-wild-card-then-wait-to-celebrate|date=September 26, 2014|accessdate=October 8, 2014|first=Ryan|last=Hood|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>  Both were the result of separate Brewers' losses to Cincinnati.<ref name=Buctober/><ref name=clinch/>

With Pittsburgh's postseason place secured, manager [[Clint Hurdle]] chose to start [[Gerrit Cole]] <U+2013> the team's [[Ace (baseball)|ace]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Giants rout Pirates in NL wild-card game|url=http://www.jconline.com/story/sports/mlb/2014/10/01/giants-rout-pirates-nl-wild-card-game/16570683/|date=October 1, 2014|first=Will|last=Graves|accessdate=October 7, 2014|newspaper=Journal & Courier|location=Lafayette, Indiana}} {{subscription required}}</ref> <U+2013> in the final game of the season against the [[Cincinnati Reds]] on September 28, instead of skipping his turn in the rotation.<ref name=PG>{{cite news|title=Pirates notebook: Hurdle defends plan to use Cole|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/sports/pirates/2014/09/29/Hurdle-defends-plan-to-use-Cole/stories/201409290133|date=September 29, 2014|first=Bill|last=Brink|accessdate=October 7, 2014|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette}} {{subscription required}}</ref>  This was done in an effort to pip the Cardinals to the [[National League Central|NL Central]] division title, rather than simply settling for the wild card spot.<ref>{{cite web|title=Organization aligned in decision to start Cole|url=http://m.pirates.mlb.com/news/article/96799966/organization-aligned-in-decision-to-start-gerrit-cole|date=September 29, 2014|accessdate=October 6, 2014|first=Tom|last=Singer|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>  The Pirates also needed to rely on the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] <U+2013> which finished with the worst record in the MLB at 64<U+2013>98 (.395)<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Major League Baseball Standings and Head-to-Head|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2014-standings.shtml|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref> <U+2013> to defeat St. Louis in order to force a [[List of Major League Baseball tie-breakers|tiebreaker]].<ref name=PG/>  However, this did not come to fruition as the Cardinals narrowly won 1<U+2013>0 over the D-backs,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/ARI/ARI201409280.shtml|title=September 28, 2014 St. Louis Cardinals at Arizona Diamondbacks Play by Play and Box Score|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|date=September 28, 2014|accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref> while the Pirates lost 4<U+2013>1 to Cincinnati.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cole's 12 K's not enough as Pirates fall to Reds|url=http://pittsburgh.pirates.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2014_09_28_pitmlb_cinmlb_1&mode=recap_away&c_id=pit|date=September 28, 2014|accessdate=October 7, 2014|first=Tom|last=Singer|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>  As a result of Cole starting in Sunday's season finale, he was unable to pitch in the Wild Card Game on Wednesday.<ref name=PG/>

==The game==
[[File:Brandon Crawford on July 15, 2011.jpg|thumb|right|In the fourth inning, [[Brandon Crawford]] hit the first postseason [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] by a [[shortstop]].]]
For the Wild Card Game, the Pirates started [[Edinson Volquez]], who had a 13<U+2013>7 [[Win<U+2013>loss record (pitching)|win<U+2013>loss record]] and 3.04 [[earned run average]] (ERA) in 31 [[games started]] during the 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Edinson Volquez Statistics and History|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/v/volqued01.shtml|accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref>  Hurdle picked him over the team's other available starters <U+2013> [[Francisco Liriano]] (who would have been pitching on only three days' rest) and [[Jeff Locke]], who pitched erratically throughout the year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pirates' Volquez named starter for wild card game against Giants|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/sports/pirates/2014/09/29/Pirates-Volquez-named-starter-for-wild-card-game-against-Giants/stories/201409290197|date=September 29, 2014|first=Bill|last=Brink|accessdate=October 7, 2014|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette}} {{subscription required}}</ref>  The Giants selected left-hander [[Madison Bumgarner]], who had a 18<U+2013>10 win<U+2013>loss record and 2.98 ERA during the season, as their starting pitcher.<ref>{{cite web|title=Madison Bumgarner Statistics and History|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/bumgama01.shtml|accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref>  He was chosen over [[Jake Peavy]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Madison Bumgarner to start wild card|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|work=ESPN|agency=Associated Press|date=September 28, 2014|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/11607054/san-francisco-giants-start-madison-bumgarner-nl-wild-card-game|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Giants season in hands of bulldog Madison Bumgarner|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2014/09/30/madison-bumgarner-nl-wild-card-giants-pirates/16508165/|date=September 30, 2014|first=Jorge L.|last=Ortiz|accessdate=October 7, 2014|newspaper=USA Today}}</ref> given the southpaw's superior record on the road during the season; Bumgarner compiled an 11<U+2013>4 win<U+2013>loss record with a 2.22 ERA on the road, compared to a 7<U+2013>6 record and 4.03 ERA at [[AT&T Park]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Giants will be on the road for wild-card game, but where?|url=http://www.sacbee.com/2014/09/27/6740120/giants-will-be-on-the-road-for.html|date=September 27, 2014|first=Matt|last=Kawahara|accessdate=October 7, 2014|newspaper=The Sacramento Bee}}</ref>

The first third of the game was a tight scoreless [[Glossary of baseball (P)#pitchers.27 duel|pitcher's duel]] between Volquez and Bumgarner,<ref name=box>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PIT/PIT201410010.shtml|title=October 1, 2014 National League Wild Card (NLWC) Game 1, Giants at Pirates|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|date=October 1, 2014|accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref> with the latter needing to throw just 28 pitches <U+2013> the fewest number of pitches he has ever tossed in three consecutive innings of any game in his career.<ref name=stats>{{cite news|title=Top stats to know: Giants dominate Pirates|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|work=ESPN|date=October 2, 2014|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/statsinfo/post/_/id/96498/top-stats-to-know-giants-dominate-pirates|accessdate=October 6, 2014}}</ref>  Only one batter <U+2013> Giants' third baseman [[Pablo Sandoval]] <U+2013> was able to advance as far as second base during this time.  The game remained tied until the fourth inning, when Volquez allowed two [[Single (baseball)|singles]] and a [[Base on balls|walk]] to [[Glossary of baseball (B)#bases loaded|load the bases]].  The subsequent batter, [[Brandon Crawford]], hit a grand slam.<ref name=box/>  This was the first [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] hit by a [[shortstop]] in [[Major League Baseball postseason|postseason]] history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crawford sparks Giants with first playoff slam by shortstop|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/97247530/giants-brandon-crawford-first-shortstop-to-hit-grand-slam-in-postseason-history|date=October 2, 2014|accessdate=October 3, 2014|first=Paul|last=Casella|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>  Up until this point, players from all other [[Baseball positions|positions in baseball]]&nbsp;<U+2013> including [[pitcher]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Dave McNally, 60, Early Free Agent, Dies|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/03/sports/dave-mcnally-60-early-free-agent-dies.html|date=December 3, 2002|first=Richard|last=Goldstein|accessdate=October 3, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sabr.org/bioproj/person/11d59b62|title=Dave McNally|first=Mark|last=Armour|work=The Baseball Biography Project|publisher=Society for American Baseball Research|accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref> <U+2013> had hit postseason grand slams.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pirates ousted as Giants' power backs Madison Bumgarner shutout|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|work=ESPN|agency=Associated Press|date=October 1, 2014|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=341001123|accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref>  Volquez pitched until the top of the sixth inning, when he gave up a walk and was replaced by [[Justin Wilson (baseball)|Justin Wilson]], who promptly threw a [[wild pitch]]. Wilson then allowed the [[inherited runner]] to score on a [[run batted in]] (RBI) single by [[Brandon Belt]], who ended up driving in two more runs in the seventh inning with another single.  The Giants added their final run of the game with an RBI single by [[Buster Posey]] in the top of the eighth.<ref name=box/>

The Pirates, who had struggled to score a run off Bumgarner throughout the entire game, came closest in the bottom of the eighth inning.  With one out, they had [[Glossary of baseball (R)#runners at the corners|runners at the corners]] after two [[Error (baseball)|errors]] and a single.<ref name=box/>  He extinguished the threat by striking out [[Jordy Mercer]] and having reigning [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|NL MVP]] [[Andrew McCutchen]] ground into a force out.<ref>{{cite web|title=Giants, MadBum slam Pirates in Wild Card|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2014_10_01_sfnmlb_pitmlb_1&mode=recap_away&c_id=sf|date=October 2, 2014|accessdate=October 3, 2014|first=Chris|last=Haft|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>  Although Giants manager [[Bruce Bochy]] instructed [[Closer (baseball)|closer]] [[Sergio Romo]] to warm up in the [[bullpen]]<ref>{{cite news|title=NL wild card: Madison Bumgarner throws complete game as Giants beat Pirates, 8<U+2013>0|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/nationals/nl-wild-card-madison-bumgarner-throws-complete-game-as-giants-beat-pirates-8-0/2014/10/01/fb414de6-49b4-11e4-891d-713f052086a0_story.html|date=October 1, 2014|first=Barry|last=Svrluga|accessdate=October 3, 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref> <U+2013> in preparation of removing Bumgarner from the game&nbsp;<U+2013> the starter insisted on continuing into the bottom of the ninth.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crawford<U+2019>s slam sets tone as Giants top Pirates 8<U+2013>0|url=http://www.sfgate.com/giants/article/Crawford-s-slam-sets-tone-as-Giants-top-Pirates-5795449.php|date=October 2, 2014|first=Henry|last=Schulman|accessdate=October 3, 2014|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>  He proceeded to pitch a perfect inning to finish the [[Shutouts in baseball|shutout]], giving up four singles and one walk while striking out 10 during the [[complete game]].<ref name=box/>  In contrast, the entire Pirates' lineup batted .125 that night;<ref name=box/> excluding [[Josh Harrison]]'s 2-for-4 performance, the rest of the team hit 2-for-28 (.071).<ref name=stats/>

