==Aftermath==
By winning the game, San Francisco secured the team's seventh NLDS appearance in franchise history, since the permanent implementation of the Division Series after the [[1994 Major League Baseball season|1994 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/|title=World Series Winners, Records, and Results and Postseason Series|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=October 6, 2014}}</ref>  They also extended their record for most consecutive victories in postseason elimination games to seven.  This tied the [[Kansas City Royals]], who had just extended their record [[2014 American League Wild Card Game|the night before]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Did You Know? 2014 NL Wild Card Game|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/97270440/did-you-know-2014-nl-wild-card-game|date=October 2, 2014|accessdate=October 3, 2014|first=Manny|last=Randhawa|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>  Bumgarner became just the third pitcher&nbsp;<U+2013> after [[Sandy Koufax]] (in the [[1965 World Series]]) and [[Justin Verlander]] (in the [[2012 American League Division Series]])<ref name=stats/>&nbsp;<U+2013> to pitch a shutout with at least 10 strikeouts in a deciding postseason game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bumgarner's October masterpiece|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|work=ESPN|first=Jayson|last=Stark|date=October 2, 2014|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs/2014/story/_/id/11626019/madison-bumgarner-new-october-masterpiece|accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref>

The Giants played the [[Washington Nationals]] in the NLDS.  The second game of that series saw San Francisco win 2<U+2013>1 after 18 innings.  Lasting 6 hours and 23 minutes, it was the longest postseason game in history in terms of time elapsed,<ref>{{cite web|title=Giants, Nats battle in longest playoff game in history|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/97621636/giants-nats-battle-in-longest-playoff-game-in-history|date=October 2, 2014|accessdate=October 3, 2014|first=Manny|last=Randhawa|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref> and was the joint-longest in terms of innings (tied with the [[2005 National League Division Series|2005 NLDS]] game between the [[Houston Astros]] and the Braves).<ref>{{cite web|title=Giants-Nationals, Game 2: Did you know?|url=http://m.giants.mlb.com/news/article/97623440/giants-nationals-game-2-did-you-know|date=October 5, 2014|accessdate=October 8, 2014|first=Ryan|last=Hood|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>  Although the Nationals won the next game against Bumgarner <U+2013> ending the Giants' NL record of 10 consecutive postseason games won<ref>{{cite web|title=Nationals-Giants Game 3: Did You Know?|url=http://m.giants.mlb.com/news/article/97790976/nationals-giants-game-3-did-you-know|date=October 7, 2014|accessdate=October 8, 2014|first=Andrew|last=Simon|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref> <U+2013> San Francisco triumphed in Game 4 to clinch the series 3<U+2013>1 and advance to the [[2014 National League Championship Series|NL Championship Series]] (NLCS).<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 NL Division Series (3<U+2013>1): San Francisco Giants (88<U+2013>74) over Washington Nationals (96<U+2013>66)|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2014_NLDS1.shtml|accessdate=October 8, 2014}}</ref>

The NLCS was played between Giants and the St. Louis Cardinals in a rematch of the [[2012 National League Championship Series|NLCS two years before]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cardinals And Giants Advance To NLCS, Will Play Each Other Saturday|url=http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/10/08/354463972/cardinals-and-giants-advance-to-nlcs-will-play-each-other-saturday|date=October 8, 2014|accessdate=October 8, 2014|first1=Chris|last1=Hopkins|first2=Doreen|last2=McCallister|work=NPR|publisher=National Public Radio, Inc.}}</ref>  The Giants won the series 4<U+2013>1, attaining the [[List of National League pennant winners|NL pennant]] and advancing to the [[2014 World Series|World Series]] for the third time in five years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Giants among men: SF walks off to win NL pennant|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2014_10_16_slnmlb_sfnmlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=sf|date=October 17, 2014|accessdate=October 17, 2014|first=Chris|last=Haft|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref>  They faced the [[Kansas City Royals]] in only the second Fall Classic played between two wild card teams, and the first since the [[2002 World Series]] when San Francisco lost to the [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|Anaheim Angels]] in seven games.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wild World Series: Perfect Royals vs tested Giants|url=http://www.bigstory.ap.org/article/2edee4aefddb44ccaae5acccbceb116f/wild-world-series-perfect-royals-vs-tested-giants|date=October 17, 2014|first=Ben|last=Walker|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=October 17, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017052233/http://www.bigstory.ap.org/article/2edee4aefddb44ccaae5acccbceb116f/wild-world-series-perfect-royals-vs-tested-giants|archivedate=October 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=From wild cards to World Series, Giants, Royals endured|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2014/10/16/royals-giants-mlb-wild-card-teams/17385731/|date=September 16, 2014|first=Jorge L.|last=Ortiz|accessdate=October 17, 2014|newspaper=USA Today}}</ref> The Giants won the series in seven games, becoming the second Wild Card World Series winner to win the World Series after being on the losing end in the first such series in 2002.

